WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-CA

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:03.603
[ <00:00:00.433><c>♪</c><00:00:00.500><c>♪</c><00:00:00.533><c> ]</c>

00:00:03.603 --> 00:00:05.471
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: We're inside
farmers' markets.

00:00:05.471 --> 00:00:07.240
&gt;&gt; The home grown ones,
are they yours then, or...?

00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:09.109
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Are you
really buying direct

00:00:09.109 --> 00:00:10.142
from the farm?

00:00:10.142 --> 00:00:12.478
Or are they feeding you lies?

00:00:12.478 --> 00:00:14.079
&gt;&gt; What's the farm called?

00:00:14.079 --> 00:00:15.582
&gt;&gt; Uh, Koornneef.

00:00:15.582 --> 00:00:18.117 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: So that's Koornneef
Produce, right over there.

00:00:18.117 --> 00:00:20.486
Not a family farm after all.

00:00:20.486 --> 00:00:22.422
Tracking down the truth.

00:00:22.422 --> 00:00:23.756
Consumers are paying
a premium for your

00:00:23.756 --> 00:00:26.559
product because they
think that you grew it.

00:00:26.559 --> 00:00:28.628
Are you ripping people off?

00:00:28.628 --> 00:00:30.763
This is your Marketplace.

00:00:30.763 --> 00:00:33.432
[ ♪♪ ]

00:00:33.432 --> 00:00:36.002
[ Chickens Clucking ]

00:00:36.002 --> 00:00:38.671
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: This is probably
where you think food from your

00:00:38.671 --> 00:00:40.939
local farmers' market
comes from.

00:00:40.939 --> 00:00:43.643
[ ♪♪ ]

00:00:43.643 --> 00:00:46.479
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: But Lauren Nurse
wants you to know the truth.

00:00:46.479 --> 00:00:48.347
&gt;&gt; I think people go to the
market to have relationships

00:00:48.347 --> 00:00:51.250
with farmers and they think that
the people they're buying food

00:00:51.250 --> 00:00:53.252
from are farmers, like me.

00:00:53.252 --> 00:00:55.388
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: And she's
not alone.

00:00:57.290 --> 00:00:58.757
&gt;&gt; My name is Sam McClain.

00:00:58.757 --> 00:01:03.696
I've been farming for 27 years.

00:01:03.696 --> 00:01:05.832
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: These farmers
are letting you in on an

00:01:05.832 --> 00:01:07.567
industry secret.

00:01:07.567 --> 00:01:10.470
The people you are buying
from at your market may not be

00:01:10.470 --> 00:01:13.173
farmers at all.

00:01:13.173 --> 00:01:16.375
&gt;&gt; I think it is just being
misled or deceived,

00:01:16.375 --> 00:01:21.714
and...it doesn't
sit right with me.

00:01:21.714 --> 00:01:23.482
&gt;&gt; People at the market don't
know that and they're buying

00:01:23.482 --> 00:01:27.754
that food and they are being
lied to, so it's a real issue.

00:01:27.754 --> 00:01:30.990
And I am actually surprised that
it is not talked about more and

00:01:30.990 --> 00:01:35.895
I'm actually surprised
that, yeah, people don't know.

00:01:35.895 --> 00:01:37.529
People don't know.

00:01:37.529 --> 00:01:39.832
[ ♪♪ ]

00:01:39.832 --> 00:01:41.301
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: I'm one of
those people.

00:01:41.301 --> 00:01:43.636
I shop at farmer's
markets all the time.

00:01:43.636 --> 00:01:46.405
You selling a lot of berries,
though, today?

00:01:46.405 --> 00:01:50.610
And I had no idea there may be
people who didn't actually grow

00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:52.244
the food themselves.

00:01:52.244 --> 00:01:53.479
Can I try one of your berries?

00:01:53.479 --> 00:01:54.480
&gt;&gt; Yes, of course.

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:55.582
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Yeah?

00:01:55.582 --> 00:01:57.650
&gt;&gt; They're called resellers
and we're told they're

00:01:57.650 --> 00:02:00.086
not always
upfront about it.

00:02:00.086 --> 00:02:01.787
&gt;&gt; All good for your health.

00:02:01.787 --> 00:02:02.788
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: So, our plan...

00:02:02.788 --> 00:02:03.823
&gt;&gt; This is it coming up, here.

00:02:03.823 --> 00:02:06.125
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: ..visit as
many markets as we can

00:02:06.125 --> 00:02:08.060
across Ontario.

00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:10.530
&gt;&gt; Just gonna turn all this on.

00:02:10.530 --> 00:02:14.033
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: These markets
are a billion dollar industry.

00:02:14.033 --> 00:02:16.202
But largely unregulated.

00:02:16.202 --> 00:02:17.203
&gt;&gt; Hi, how is it going?

00:02:17.203 --> 00:02:18.471
&gt;&gt; Hi, how are you.

00:02:18.471 --> 00:02:21.273
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: So, we're going to
ask each vendor what they grow.

00:02:21.273 --> 00:02:22.909
&gt;&gt; Trying to go local today.

00:02:22.909 --> 00:02:24.043
Thank you.

00:02:24.043 --> 00:02:25.945
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: And then see
if their claims check out.

00:02:33.052 --> 00:02:34.654 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: It doesn't
take long for us to start

00:02:34.654 --> 00:02:36.655
getting suspicious.

00:02:36.655 --> 00:02:39.225
[ ♪♪ ]

00:02:39.225 --> 00:02:41.393
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: At a busy
market in downtown Toronto,

00:02:41.393 --> 00:02:44.864
this vendor advertises his
produce as homegrown.

00:02:50.003 --> 00:02:51.036
But for field, yes.

00:02:51.036 --> 00:02:54.107
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Added bonus,
it is chemical free.

00:02:54.107 --> 00:02:55.141
&gt;&gt; Is it from your place?

00:02:55.141 --> 00:02:56.575
&gt;&gt; Yep.

00:02:56.575 --> 00:02:59.178
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: He says
it is there is.

00:02:59.178 --> 00:03:02.681 align:start position:0%
But we spot boxes with a
different name under the table.

00:03:02.681 --> 00:03:05.018
And when we call
the name on that box,

00:03:05.018 --> 00:03:09.088
we discover it leads back to a
wholesaler who says those

00:03:09.088 --> 00:03:12.257
tomatoes weren't
sold as pesticide free.

00:03:12.257 --> 00:03:16.195 align:start position:0%
The owner later says he tries
to label produce that isn't his.

00:03:16.195 --> 00:03:18.731
[ ♪♪ ]

00:03:18.731 --> 00:03:21.367
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: That wasn't the
only vendor it seems is trying

00:03:21.367 --> 00:03:23.803
to mislead us.

00:03:36.682 --> 00:03:39.585
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: At this market,
the vendor says the name of his

00:03:39.585 --> 00:03:41.587
family farm is Koornneef...

00:03:41.587 --> 00:03:44.791
But we saw produce
with that name at at least 3

00:03:44.791 --> 00:03:51.463
other markets!

00:03:51.463 --> 00:03:53.699
&gt;&gt; the other place we spot
Koornneef,

00:03:53.699 --> 00:03:57.202
is at the grocery store.

00:03:57.202 --> 00:03:58.570
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: So that is
Koornneef produce

00:03:58.570 --> 00:03:59.939
right over there.

00:03:59.939 --> 00:04:02.007
Not a family farm after all.

00:04:02.007 --> 00:04:05.445
In fact Koornneef is a large
scale wholesaler and you can

00:04:05.445 --> 00:04:09.248
find them right here at
Ontario's food terminal.

00:04:09.248 --> 00:04:11.384
When we follow up with
the owner of that stall

00:04:11.384 --> 00:04:13.152
they won't comment.

00:04:13.152 --> 00:04:17.289
And they won't tell us
if they grow anything at all.

00:04:17.289 --> 00:04:22.461
[ ♪♪ ]

00:04:22.461 --> 00:04:24.997
&gt;&gt; Over time it has
become much harder work.

00:04:24.997 --> 00:04:28.067
Much-needed, a much larger
acreage and some people have

00:04:28.067 --> 00:04:31.270
found it easier to just go to
the terminal and bring the

00:04:31.270 --> 00:04:32.939
produce in.

00:04:32.939 --> 00:04:36.375
So we have some pollen
in these cells up here.

00:04:36.375 --> 00:04:40.846 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; My name is Astrid Manske,
we gather honey in the

00:04:40.846 --> 00:04:44.683
Otonabee township and east.

00:04:44.683 --> 00:04:47.586
&gt;&gt; People are coming
not for the grocery store,

00:04:47.586 --> 00:04:50.222
if you go to the grocery
store if they wanted that.

00:04:50.222 --> 00:04:52.058
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: But at
market after market,

00:04:52.058 --> 00:04:57.062
we find stickers usually
seen at the grocery store.

00:04:57.062 --> 00:05:00.833
And even then, some vendors
claim the produce is theirs.

00:05:05.938 --> 00:05:08.473
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: But, the sticker we
spot here and at other markets

00:05:08.473 --> 00:05:10.509
all belong to the same producer.

00:05:10.509 --> 00:05:11.510
&gt;&gt; Red Sun.

00:05:11.510 --> 00:05:12.779
Red Sun.

00:05:12.779 --> 00:05:17.182
Red Sun, Canada.

00:05:17.182 --> 00:05:19.185
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: So that's who we
are tracking down next.

00:05:19.185 --> 00:05:21.988
Red Sun is a
multinational company based in

00:05:21.988 --> 00:05:24.157
Kingsville, Ontario.

00:05:24.157 --> 00:05:28.061
There is over 1700
green houses there.

00:05:28.061 --> 00:05:30.196
&gt;&gt; So this total farm as
I think around 27 acres.

00:05:30.196 --> 00:05:31.197
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Oh, wow.

00:05:31.197 --> 00:05:33.932
This is not where most
people think their local

00:05:33.932 --> 00:05:37.336
farmers' market
food is coming from.

00:05:37.336 --> 00:05:39.138
&gt;&gt; Yeah, you can see the
temperature change?

00:05:39.138 --> 00:05:41.106
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Yeah, it is
much cooler in here.

00:05:41.106 --> 00:05:43.376
&gt;&gt; The Red Sun president, Jim
Dimmena, doesn't like hearing

00:05:43.376 --> 00:05:46.745
vendors are passing off his
produce as their own.

00:05:46.745 --> 00:05:48.581
&gt;&gt; I'm a little
troubled with that.

00:05:48.581 --> 00:05:50.949
We spend a lot of money and
time growing our products.

00:05:50.949 --> 00:05:52.985
We're well over a
million dollars an acre.

00:05:52.985 --> 00:05:54.420
So it's not a just a,

00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:56.322
"I think I'll be a greenhouse
grower today."

00:05:56.322 --> 00:05:57.990
That's a serious
serious number.

00:05:57.990 --> 00:06:00.860
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Most of their
product is sold directly to

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:02.128
grocery stores.

00:06:02.128 --> 00:06:05.832
Produce that doesn't make
the cut is sold off cheaper.

00:06:05.832 --> 00:06:07.900
&gt;&gt; It might be misshapen,
it might be too small or maybe

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:08.900
even too big.

00:06:08.900 --> 00:06:10.703
So that finds its way to
a wholesale market

00:06:10.703 --> 00:06:14.273
and maybe somebody
would pick that up.

00:06:14.273 --> 00:06:15.974
Buy that from a wholesaler.

00:06:15.974 --> 00:06:19.745
And then, in turn, sell it to a,
you know, to a farmers' market

00:06:19.745 --> 00:06:20.913
or something like that.

00:06:23.915 --> 00:06:25.184
[ ♪♪ ]

00:06:25.184 --> 00:06:27.953
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: At some markets,
we also find wholesale produce

00:06:27.953 --> 00:06:30.556
that is not from Canada at all.

00:06:37.896 --> 00:06:40.900
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: This vendor says
these peppers are local but the

00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:44.937
sticker leads back to a
large grower in Mexico.

00:06:44.937 --> 00:06:48.140
The vendor later tells
us he didn't know.

00:06:48.140 --> 00:06:52.244 align:start position:0%
Hard to believe, but we find
lots of international produce at

00:06:52.244 --> 00:06:54.647
so-called local
farmers' markets.

00:06:58.150 --> 00:06:59.051
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:07:01.653 --> 00:07:03.422
[ ♪♪ ]

00:07:03.422 --> 00:07:06.158
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: So far in our test,
we have found reselling at eight

00:07:06.158 --> 00:07:09.428
out of the ten markets
we have visited.

00:07:09.428 --> 00:07:13.165
Some resellers are upfront,
but at four markets we catch

00:07:13.165 --> 00:07:15.000
vendors twisting the truth.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.170
[ ♪♪ ]

00:07:18.170 --> 00:07:20.439
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Our last stop
is Peterborough's

00:07:20.439 --> 00:07:22.040
Saturday market.

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:26.279 align:start position:0%
It's one of the largest farmers'
markets in the province.

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:30.249
It's also at the centre of a
battle between farmers

00:07:30.249 --> 00:07:31.784
and resellers.

00:07:31.784 --> 00:07:34.821
Headlines in the local paper
highlight the fight that's

00:07:34.821 --> 00:07:35.921
been brewing.

00:07:35.921 --> 00:07:38.324
[ ♪♪ ]

00:07:38.324 --> 00:07:40.793
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: When we head in,
we're not sure what to expect.

00:07:45.231 --> 00:07:48.033
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: We visit a range
of vendors and get a range

00:07:48.033 --> 00:07:48.935
of answers.

00:07:53.439 --> 00:07:55.941 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Kent Farms is
one of the largest vendors with

00:07:55.941 --> 00:07:57.810
two large stalls.

00:07:57.810 --> 00:07:59.245
One run by James Kent.

00:08:05.651 --> 00:08:07.320
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: The other
by Brent Kent.

00:08:14.427 --> 00:08:16.528
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: They tell us
everything is grown by them

00:08:16.528 --> 00:08:18.564
or neighbouring farms.

00:08:18.564 --> 00:08:21.501
But after seeing stickers
like these again...

00:08:24.403 --> 00:08:25.438
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: And again.

00:08:28.006 --> 00:08:29.342
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: We've got doubts.

00:08:33.446 --> 00:08:35.615 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: It's time to
check things out for ourselves.

00:08:42.754 --> 00:08:43.955
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: So there it is.

00:08:43.955 --> 00:08:47.192
[ ♪♪ ]

00:08:47.192 --> 00:08:50.395 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: So this is the
property record check which says

00:08:50.395 --> 00:08:56.669
that all of this along here
and there is the Kent's.

00:08:56.669 --> 00:08:57.936
Just corn.

00:08:57.936 --> 00:08:59.839
[ ♪♪ ]

00:09:06.111 --> 00:09:07.112
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Wow.

00:09:07.112 --> 00:09:09.849
Not a whole lot here other
than tractor beds.

00:09:09.849 --> 00:09:13.218
It is hard to know if we're
seeing everything for sure

00:09:13.218 --> 00:09:15.654
because I can't see
beyond those trees.

00:09:15.654 --> 00:09:17.890
But the only crop
I can see is corn.

00:09:19.725 --> 00:09:21.160
We stay on the Kents' trail.

00:09:22.828 --> 00:09:24.664
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: And our
investigation heads south

00:09:24.664 --> 00:09:25.697
of the border.

00:09:25.697 --> 00:09:27.966
Where reselling
could mean jail time.

00:09:27.966 --> 00:09:29.735
&gt;&gt; We're trying
to prevent fraud.

00:09:29.735 --> 00:09:32.337
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: This is
your Marketplace.

00:09:32.337 --> 00:09:34.774
[ ♪♪ ]

00:09:34.774 --> 00:09:37.275
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: Fresh from
this farm or fresh lies?

00:09:37.275 --> 00:09:40.045
[ ♪♪ ]

00:09:40.045 --> 00:09:42.948
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: We are tracking the
food you buy at farmers' markets

00:09:42.948 --> 00:09:44.649
back to its source.

00:09:44.649 --> 00:09:47.152
[ ♪♪ ]

00:09:47.152 --> 00:09:49.421
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: For Lauren Nurse
that leads to her farm just

00:09:49.421 --> 00:09:51.656
outside Peterborough, Ontario.

00:09:51.656 --> 00:09:54.860
[ ♪♪ ]

00:09:54.860 --> 00:09:56.161
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: But for
other vendors,

00:09:56.161 --> 00:09:58.464
we've discovered,
that trail could lead to the

00:09:58.464 --> 00:10:00.799
Ontario food terminal.

00:10:00.799 --> 00:10:03.168
Canada's largest wholesaler.

00:10:03.168 --> 00:10:05.071
[ ♪♪ ]

00:10:13.878 --> 00:10:15.881
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: We're here early.

00:10:15.881 --> 00:10:18.417
The day before Peterborough's
Saturday market.

00:10:22.921 --> 00:10:25.057
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: To see if
anyone familiar shows up.

00:10:42.807 --> 00:10:44.710
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: There's James Kent.

00:10:44.710 --> 00:10:47.379
He's told us, he grows
what he sells, but the

00:10:47.379 --> 00:10:50.249
day before market,
he isn't in the fields.

00:10:50.249 --> 00:10:51.583
He's here.

00:10:51.583 --> 00:10:53.886
[ ♪♪ ]

00:11:05.163 --> 00:11:07.933
[ ♪♪ ]

00:11:11.236 --> 00:11:13.272 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: The next day we're
at the market when the

00:11:13.272 --> 00:11:14.606
Kents arrive.

00:11:14.606 --> 00:11:16.975
[ ♪♪ ]

00:11:16.975 --> 00:11:20.479
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: We watch as boxes
that look just like those loaded

00:11:20.479 --> 00:11:24.650
at the terminal
get unloaded here.

00:11:24.650 --> 00:11:28.053
And it's not just his own
stall James is stocking.

00:11:28.053 --> 00:11:32.258
He also makes deliveries to
Brent Kent and another vendor

00:11:32.258 --> 00:11:34.926
at the market.

00:11:34.926 --> 00:11:38.164
Zucchinis are transferred into
market friendly bushels.

00:11:41.099 --> 00:11:43.235
Carrots unpacked from plastic.

00:11:45.737 --> 00:11:48.840
And this time,
those stickers are peeled off.

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:51.577
[ ♪♪ ]

00:11:53.645 --> 00:11:55.948
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: The market fills
with shoppers and

00:11:55.948 --> 00:11:56.849
we head in too.

00:12:16.501 --> 00:12:19.004
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: We found no
evidence of radishes across

00:12:19.004 --> 00:12:21.474
from the Kents'.

00:12:21.474 --> 00:12:25.077
Everything across the street
is just I don't know,

00:12:25.077 --> 00:12:27.079
wild vegetation.

00:12:27.079 --> 00:12:30.916
But we did see over half a
dozen boxes of radishes the

00:12:30.916 --> 00:12:33.151
day before.

00:12:33.151 --> 00:12:37.255
Alongside them, a variety of
produce including zucchinis

00:12:37.255 --> 00:12:38.624
and peppers.

00:12:58.444 --> 00:13:00.712
&gt;&gt; There's no difference
between food that you

00:13:00.712 --> 00:13:03.549
buy at the grocery store and
food at the farmers' market if

00:13:03.549 --> 00:13:05.417
it all comes from the
food terminal.

00:13:05.417 --> 00:13:06.752
It's the same food.

00:13:06.752 --> 00:13:10.255
So people are being duped.

00:13:10.255 --> 00:13:12.357
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: But there is a
difference when it comes

00:13:12.357 --> 00:13:13.792
to price.

00:13:13.792 --> 00:13:16.261
Zucchinis and peppers
the Kents were selling,

00:13:16.261 --> 00:13:19.665
cost 50% more than what
we found at local

00:13:19.665 --> 00:13:22.768
stores that same day.

00:13:22.768 --> 00:13:26.572
A higher price point, but still
cheap enough to make it hard for

00:13:26.572 --> 00:13:28.674
farmers to compete.

00:13:28.674 --> 00:13:32.711
&gt;&gt; It's our main sales venue
and so when someone is

00:13:32.711 --> 00:13:36.048
kind of, essentially,
completely undercutting us at

00:13:36.048 --> 00:13:37.716
every step of the way,

00:13:37.716 --> 00:13:39.985
that really affects
our bottom line.

00:13:39.985 --> 00:13:43.188
&gt;&gt; Charlsie: For Sam
and Astrid, it's personal.

00:13:43.188 --> 00:13:45.491
They sell at the Peterborough
Saturday farmers' market

00:13:45.491 --> 00:13:48.894
alongside the Kents.

00:13:48.894 --> 00:13:51.129
&gt;&gt; It's important to the
customers that a farmers'

00:13:51.129 --> 00:13:54.033
market be a farmers' market
